The main problem with your approach is the fact that using `outerHTML` and `innerHTML` (which is used internally by `.html()`) for creating / moving / copying elements is kind of like serializing and de-serializing your HTML DOM tree. This works for the HTML elements themselves, however, it does not preserve event listener. Hence, the listeners you attached to the elements in your function `createNodeElement` are lost during this process. This is a variation of other questions like, e.g. [*&quot;Is it possible to append to innerHTML without destroying descendants&#39; event listeners?&quot;*](/q/595808). 

If you take a step back and re-read the D3 API [docs][1] you will realize that you are in fact almost there: D3 provides means to append native DOM nodes to a selection: 

&gt; *selection*.**append**(*type*) [&lt;&gt;][1]
&gt;
&gt; If the specified *type* is a function, it is evaluated for each selected element, in order, being passed the current datum (*d*), the current index (*i*), and the current group (*nodes*), with *this* as the current DOM element (*nodes*[*i*]). This function should return an element to be appended.

If you would like to stick to your implementation of `createNodeElement` to create an element by using native JS methods, you can simply pass that function to `selection.append()` as it returns a newly created node along with its `&lt;img&gt;` child node. Your code can thus be simplified to:

    var nodes = g.selectAll(&quot;foreignObject&quot;)
        /* styling omitted */
      .append(&quot;xhtml:div&quot;)
        .attr(&quot;class&quot;, &quot;outer&quot;)
      .append(createNodeElement);

Because only references to DOM nodes are passed around all event listeners attached to the elements will also be preserved.

  [1]: https://github.com/d3/d3-selection/blob/master/src/selection/append.js

